WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.272 --> 00:00:07.036
- (GRUNTS)
- (KNIVES CLATTER)

2
00:00:07.608 --> 00:00:09.328
Tell me again how you
don't need a Guardian.

3
00:00:09.576 --> 00:00:10.703
(GROANS)

4
00:00:10.777 --> 00:00:14.145
- Flynn. that wound is bad!
- Excalibur.

5
00:00:14.214 --> 00:00:16.445
Lamia got the crown and
she had control over Excalibur.

6
00:00:16.517 --> 00:00:17.827
- Let me treat the bleeding.
- You can't treat it.

7
00:00:17.851 --> 00:00:19.251
It's a magical
wound. I need. um...

8
00:00:20.554 --> 00:00:21.954
Wait! We got to
go find Cassandra.

9
00:00:22.022 --> 00:00:23.957
No! She's the one
who let them in! Ugh!

10
00:00:24.491 --> 00:00:26.926
Well. my lack of faith
in humanity is restored.

11
00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:31.591
(GAGS)

12
00:00:32.232 --> 00:00:34.428
Yeah. that's better.
That helps with pain.

13
00:00:34.501 --> 00:00:36.436
- The bleeding stopped!
- Slowed. Not stopped.

14
00:00:36.503 --> 00:00:38.062
Bathsheba's oil of healing.

15
00:00:38.138 --> 00:00:39.716
If it had been an ordinary
wound it would've stopped it.

16
00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:40.740
but it's a magical wound

17
00:00:40.807 --> 00:00:42.952
so it's going to slow it long
enough so that we can find Charlene.

18
00:00:42.976 --> 00:00:44.308
I passed her in the shelves.

19
00:00:44.378 --> 00:00:46.847
She said something about
meeting her deep in the Library.

20
00:00:46.914 --> 00:00:48.883
Something about
the Corridor of Doors?

21
00:00:49.383 --> 00:00:51.011
Let's go. Let's go!

22
00:01:01.228 --> 00:01:03.273
Any artifacts which can
move. prep them for transport.

23
00:01:03.297 --> 00:01:04.297
MAN: Yes. ma'am.

24
00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:08.193
Did you really have to do that?

25
00:01:09.403 --> 00:01:12.498
LAMIA: You've seen the power
the Librarians are hiding down here.

26
00:01:12.573 --> 00:01:16.476
How much knowledge is locked away.
far from the people it can help the most.

27
00:01:16.543 --> 00:01:18.910
So. you're telling me
that you're the good guys?

28
00:01:19.513 --> 00:01:22.677
We're going to use the Library's
powers to change the world.

29
00:01:22.950 --> 00:01:24.646
- Let's go.
- Grab this.

30
00:01:31.992 --> 00:01:33.392
EZEKIEL: How
big is this Library?

31
00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:34.826
FLYNN: As big
as we need it to be.

32
00:01:35.462 --> 00:01:37.124
(BELL TOLLING)

33
00:01:37.197 --> 00:01:39.393
Oh. no. That's the
countdown clock.

34
00:01:39.466 --> 00:01:41.628
Flynn. what happens
when the bell stops?

35
00:01:41.702 --> 00:01:42.702
Charlene. no!

36
00:01:52.179 --> 00:01:53.408
MAN: Get out of here!

37
00:01:55.349 --> 00:01:57.509
You mean the Library is cut
off from the outside world?

38
00:01:57.551 --> 00:02:00.646
- Get out! Grab what you can and get out!
- MAN: Come on!

39
00:02:00.721 --> 00:02:02.212
You mean it's like locked doors?

40
00:02:02.289 --> 00:02:04.383
Look around you. girl!

41
00:02:04.458 --> 00:02:07.018
Can anything this big
really just lie underneath

42
00:02:07.094 --> 00:02:08.392
the streets of New York City?

43
00:02:08.462 --> 00:02:11.261
The Library exists in its
own pocket dimension.

44
00:02:11.331 --> 00:02:12.993
anchored to our reality here.

45
00:02:13.066 --> 00:02:14.694
at this single physical place.

46
00:02:15.569 --> 00:02:17.663
And the first Librarian
just cut the anchor chain.

47
00:02:19.973 --> 00:02:21.999
(BELL TOLLING)

48
00:02:23.777 --> 00:02:25.109
- What now?
- Four bells.

49
00:02:25.712 --> 00:02:28.152
I don't know. I've never been
this deep in the Library before.

50
00:02:28.415 --> 00:02:29.439
That's three bells.

51
00:02:29.516 --> 00:02:31.694
- Charlene. She'll know what to do.
- COLONEL BAIRD: She's not coming.

52
00:02:31.718 --> 00:02:34.085
- All right. Judson. he's always here!
- He's not coming!

53
00:02:34.154 --> 00:02:35.554
Two bells! Pick a door!

54
00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:54.838
What the hell?

55
00:02:55.842 --> 00:02:57.708
Judson! Charlene!

56
00:03:08.155 --> 00:03:09.555
Where are we?

57
00:03:09.623 --> 00:03:11.285
EZEKIEL: When are we?

58
00:03:11.358 --> 00:03:13.020
It's day. We time-traveled.

59
00:03:14.294 --> 00:03:16.229
Time travel. Ugh.

60
00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:18.896
Time travel's not all
it's cracked up to be.

61
00:03:21.635 --> 00:03:23.194
Hey. Blood. Mine.

62
00:03:23.503 --> 00:03:27.133
It's crimson. I need
to eat more calcium.

63
00:03:28.608 --> 00:03:30.304
- Whoa.
- Let's not panic.

64
00:03:30.377 --> 00:03:31.688
There's a logical
way to approach

65
00:03:31.712 --> 00:03:33.112
- being trapped in the past.
- Okay.

66
00:03:33.180 --> 00:03:36.275
We find the local king. tell
him about our powerful magic.

67
00:03:36.349 --> 00:03:38.545
invent a steam engine.
and he gives us a duchy.

68
00:03:38.618 --> 00:03:41.247
Eventually. we use our superior
technology to take over the land.

69
00:03:41.321 --> 00:03:46.453
I hate to break it to you. King Jones the
First. but I got cell service. American carrier.

70
00:03:47.260 --> 00:03:50.560
Of course. We didn't travel through
time. we traveled through space.

71
00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:53.843
We came west! It's still night in New York.
but the sun's still up on the West Coast.

72
00:03:53.867 --> 00:03:55.460
GPS coming online.

73
00:03:55.535 --> 00:03:59.370
Latitude would put us exactly in

74
00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:00.864
- Oregon.
- Oregon.

75
00:04:00.941 --> 00:04:02.102
See. I still got it.

76
00:04:02.909 --> 00:04:04.149
We gotta get him to a hospital.

77
00:04:04.244 --> 00:04:06.179
Road's this way. Don't
see a hospital though.

78
00:04:06.947 --> 00:04:08.108
He's bleeding real bad.

79
00:04:08.181 --> 00:04:09.979
Well. we better get
a move on. then.

80
00:04:14.721 --> 00:04:16.519
- Hi.
- Howdy.

81
00:04:17.891 --> 00:04:20.292
Your friend does not
look well. You need a ride?

82
00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:23.853
I'm Colonel Eve Baird. Uh. do
you mind if we explain in the car?

83
00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:27.128
No need to talk. I hate to
pry into people's business.

84
00:04:28.101 --> 00:04:29.592
What were you doing out here?

85
00:04:29.669 --> 00:04:32.104
Waiting. I do that.

86
00:04:35.909 --> 00:04:37.172
(ENGINE STARTS)

87
00:04:46.319 --> 00:04:48.879
COLONEL BAIRD: Hang in
there. Flynn. How far to the hospital?

88
00:04:50.056 --> 00:04:51.922
Hospital? Oh. no. no. no. no.

89
00:04:51.992 --> 00:04:55.121
Why would we take him to a
hospital? We're almost here.

90
00:05:07.507 --> 00:05:10.909
Wait. wait. wait. We need a hospital!
He's been stabbed. He's bleeding out.

91
00:05:10.977 --> 00:05:13.105
Hospital won't do him any good.

92
00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:16.207
Wounds caused by
Excalibur don't heal. Magic!

93
00:05:25.792 --> 00:05:28.557
Wait a second. How do
you know about Excalibur?

94
00:05:28.628 --> 00:05:32.065
Please forgive the dust. Hasn't
been used in ages. of course.

95
00:05:32.532 --> 00:05:34.398
And how do you
know about magic? Ah!

96
00:05:39.206 --> 00:05:41.505
I know all about
you. Flynn Carsen.

97
00:05:41.575 --> 00:05:45.137
I don't understand.
What is this place?

98
00:05:45.212 --> 00:05:46.805
- Who are you?
- Who am I?

99
00:05:47.614 --> 00:05:50.743
Jenkins. of course.
As far as this place...

100
00:05:52.285 --> 00:05:53.285
Well.

101
00:05:56.189 --> 00:05:57.282
(SNAPS FINGERS)

102
00:06:01.728 --> 00:06:03.253
You're in the Library.

103
00:06:10.904 --> 00:06:11.963
Aw.

104
00:06:18.144 --> 00:06:20.344
Say. you wouldn't happen to
have a cold beer. would you?

105
00:06:20.447 --> 00:06:21.847
(SNIFFS) Uh. no.

106
00:06:21.915 --> 00:06:26.319
As this is the Library and
not a rodeo or a hobo camp

107
00:06:26.386 --> 00:06:28.912
or wherever it is people
like you gather in crowds.

108
00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:34.892
- Mmm-mmm. Don't! Don't move too much.
- Ow!

109
00:06:34.961 --> 00:06:36.827
What did you stuff it
there with? Duct tape?

110
00:06:36.897 --> 00:06:38.957
- Glue?
- Yes. actually.

111
00:06:39.032 --> 00:06:40.509
- The bleeding won't stop.
- No. it won't stop.

112
00:06:40.533 --> 00:06:43.002
It's a magical wound
from Excalibur.

113
00:06:43.136 --> 00:06:44.263
(SIGHS)

114
00:06:45.639 --> 00:06:47.505
Oh. God! What... (GRUNTS)

115
00:06:48.808 --> 00:06:50.709
Don't touch anything!

116
00:06:51.778 --> 00:06:53.007
I think you broke Africa.

117
00:06:53.079 --> 00:06:57.244
This is my workplace. not Judson's.
And I'm doing very important research.

118
00:06:57.317 --> 00:06:59.479
We're in the Library?
Ah! (GRUNTS)

119
00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.549
Judson! Charlene!

120
00:07:07.193 --> 00:07:09.526
- Where's the Library?
- No. no. no. this is the same room.

121
00:07:09.596 --> 00:07:11.588
Hey. I swear this
is the same room.

122
00:07:11.665 --> 00:07:13.657
Yes. of course it is.

123
00:07:16.136 --> 00:07:20.972
The main Library can only ever be anchored
to one specific place in the world.

124
00:07:21.041 --> 00:07:24.773
What if the Librarian needed to gain
access to the Library's knowledge.

125
00:07:24.844 --> 00:07:26.608
but was far from the front door?

126
00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:27.943
This is an interface.

127
00:07:28.315 --> 00:07:30.682
Judson ran the Library while
you were out here in an annex.

128
00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:34.551
Yes. Separate. but connected.

129
00:07:35.088 --> 00:07:36.147
Oh.

130
00:07:36.456 --> 00:07:37.515
Name a book.

131
00:07:37.590 --> 00:07:39.923
something you know is
only in the main Library.

132
00:07:39.993 --> 00:07:44.431
Isaac Newton's <i>Principia
Mathematica.</i> the unedited version.

133
00:07:46.466 --> 00:07:52.599
Section F. row nine. shelf AA2. right
behind the little shifty-looking fellow.

134
00:08:01.481 --> 00:08:05.179
(READING) <i>"The mathematical
principles of natural philosophy</i>

135
00:08:05.251 --> 00:08:08.710
<i>"as derived by the wondrous
thinking machines of Atlantis"?</i>

136
00:08:09.222 --> 00:08:10.850
Like I said. the
unedited version.

137
00:08:10.924 --> 00:08:12.051
I am afraid.

138
00:08:12.125 --> 00:08:18.065
as Judson has cut the connection
of the Library to the physical world.

139
00:08:18.131 --> 00:08:19.963
this room is all we have.

140
00:08:20.033 --> 00:08:24.937
Access to information. but no
way in or out of the main Library.

141
00:08:25.105 --> 00:08:27.540
Ah. typical Judson. so rash.

142
00:08:27.607 --> 00:08:29.940
Hey. watch your tone when
you speak about Judson.

143
00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:31.530
Judson and I never
agreed on anything.

144
00:08:31.578 --> 00:08:34.343
I mean. I realize that the
Library is best used for research.

145
00:08:34.414 --> 00:08:38.579
Not for gallivanting about. fighting
monsters. seducing princesses.

146
00:08:38.651 --> 00:08:40.429
- (LAUGHS)
- Oh. I'm guessing with that attitude.

147
00:08:40.453 --> 00:08:42.665
that's why you're probably
stuck out here in the Annex. huh?

148
00:08:42.689 --> 00:08:43.987
Not at the home office.

149
00:08:45.458 --> 00:08:47.654
Very happy here. It's quiet.

150
00:08:47.727 --> 00:08:49.821
I can focus on my
work. not bothered by

151
00:08:52.565 --> 00:08:54.405
the greatest collection
of magic in the world.

152
00:08:58.738 --> 00:09:00.502
I should have seen it coming.

153
00:09:01.241 --> 00:09:03.836
Cassandra. they
had leverage on her.

154
00:09:05.412 --> 00:09:07.372
I should've seen it. I
should have seen all of it.

155
00:09:09.315 --> 00:09:10.943
Why didn't Judson warn me?

156
00:09:11.451 --> 00:09:14.319
Maybe Judson trusted you
to figure it out on your own.

157
00:09:14.387 --> 00:09:17.050
How could I not see that
they were killing Librarians?

158
00:09:22.395 --> 00:09:24.921
People are dead because
I just wasn't good enough.

159
00:09:24.998 --> 00:09:26.296
You're opening your wound.

160
00:09:26.366 --> 00:09:28.460
It doesn't matter!
Magical wound.

161
00:09:30.804 --> 00:09:31.863
It won't ever heal.

162
00:09:34.307 --> 00:09:35.434
I'm going to die.

163
00:09:37.677 --> 00:09:38.677
Tell 'em.

164
00:09:39.779 --> 00:09:41.805
- (SIGHS)
- What? Tell me what?

165
00:09:46.086 --> 00:09:48.954
I can pump him full of fluids.
but if he keeps bleeding...

166
00:09:52.258 --> 00:09:53.453
Twenty-four hours.

167
00:09:54.561 --> 00:09:56.757
He's dead in 24 hours.

168
00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:59.527
Yeah. Isn't he supposed
to be in charge?

169
00:10:01.901 --> 00:10:03.426
Yeah. this is not good.

170
00:10:05.905 --> 00:10:07.498
DULAQUE: Cassandra!

171
00:10:07.574 --> 00:10:12.740
So glad you managed to avoid the
insane suicide plan of the Librarians.

172
00:10:12.812 --> 00:10:14.246
Do you know if
the others got out?

173
00:10:14.314 --> 00:10:15.714
Ezekiel and Stone?

174
00:10:16.616 --> 00:10:17.948
Well. I dearly hope so.

175
00:10:18.284 --> 00:10:23.882
You see the lengths the Librarians will go
to to hide the gift of magic from the world?

176
00:10:23.957 --> 00:10:28.759
Destroy anything. anyone.
to keep their secrets.

177
00:10:29.963 --> 00:10:31.431
If you can cure me...

178
00:10:32.966 --> 00:10:36.198
When the key is
joined to the lock

179
00:10:36.269 --> 00:10:39.671
and magic is
returned to the world.

180
00:10:43.910 --> 00:10:46.277
we can absolutely cure you.

181
00:10:48.014 --> 00:10:49.141
You have to share it.

182
00:10:49.682 --> 00:10:52.709
You have to help all of the
people that science can't save.

183
00:10:52.785 --> 00:10:54.913
Cassandra. that's
why you're here.

184
00:10:56.222 --> 00:10:58.748
To help us bring
magic back to the world

185
00:10:58.825 --> 00:11:01.761
and help those who cannot
be helped by other means.

186
00:11:04.197 --> 00:11:05.722
We're going to change the world.

187
00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:11.231
Now. you'd best
get some rest. Hmm?

188
00:11:20.180 --> 00:11:21.739
Why'd you stop me?

189
00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:25.079
New rug.

190
00:11:26.119 --> 00:11:31.387
And even with Excalibur. there are
bound to be impediments accessing the lock.

191
00:11:32.025 --> 00:11:35.689
Having a Librarian. even half
a Librarian. may prove useful.

192
00:11:38.064 --> 00:11:39.464
But mostly the rug.

193
00:11:50.343 --> 00:11:52.209
I need Flynn to
pull it together.

194
00:11:53.680 --> 00:11:56.013
I'm too new to this world.

195
00:11:56.449 --> 00:11:59.112
Well. then you need to
go and pull him together.

196
00:11:59.185 --> 00:12:00.744
You're his Guardian.

197
00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:03.380
That means more than
merely keeping him alive.

198
00:12:03.456 --> 00:12:06.654
It means keeping him in one
piece. both mentally and physically.

199
00:12:07.527 --> 00:12:09.393
Didn't do a great job of that.

200
00:12:10.096 --> 00:12:11.189
So he got stabbed.

201
00:12:12.265 --> 00:12:17.568
Librarians get stabbed and shot
and bitten and cursed all the time.

202
00:12:19.539 --> 00:12:22.941
He's gonna die. Soon.

203
00:12:23.009 --> 00:12:26.571
We're all gonna die soon
if you don't get in there.

204
00:12:27.347 --> 00:12:32.217
Now. look. Guardian. if he fell into a river.
you would reach in and pull him out. Yes?

205
00:12:32.285 --> 00:12:34.117
Before he could drown.

206
00:12:34.821 --> 00:12:37.689
Judson was everything to Flynn.

207
00:12:37.757 --> 00:12:41.717
As was Charlene who. quite
frankly. I always liked better.

208
00:12:42.262 --> 00:12:43.355
To lose them both?

209
00:12:44.464 --> 00:12:47.662
Right now. he is drowning.

210
00:12:47.734 --> 00:12:49.168
Right now.

211
00:12:51.771 --> 00:12:53.000
Go save him.

212
00:13:03.116 --> 00:13:04.516
Flynn?

213
00:13:39.819 --> 00:13:44.985
(READING) <i>"Higher Dimensional
Quantum Translocation Theory"</i>

214
00:13:46.693 --> 00:13:48.093
by Albert Einstein.

215
00:13:48.161 --> 00:13:50.289
Original edition. I think...

216
00:13:51.164 --> 00:13:53.565
I think I figured out a
way back to the Library.

217
00:13:55.368 --> 00:13:56.968
Is that really where
we should be going?

218
00:13:58.638 --> 00:14:01.107
Yeah. we've got tools there.
We've got artifacts there.

219
00:14:01.174 --> 00:14:05.407
We've got resources that we're gonna need if
we're gonna fight the Serpent Brotherhood.

220
00:14:09.182 --> 00:14:14.382
In the few days we've known each
other. I haven't seen you use any tools

221
00:14:16.055 --> 00:14:19.548
or magical
equipment or artifacts.

222
00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:22.422
Just your brain.

223
00:14:26.199 --> 00:14:28.566
That's why Judson
chose you. right?

224
00:14:30.737 --> 00:14:33.730
Your brain is a weapon

225
00:14:33.806 --> 00:14:36.537
and a tool and a library.

226
00:14:36.609 --> 00:14:38.202
all wrapped up into one.

227
00:14:39.479 --> 00:14:43.849
Judson chose you because. in
the end. you don't need anything.

228
00:14:48.154 --> 00:14:51.682
Yeah. but Charlene could
still be alive. Judson could still...

229
00:14:51.758 --> 00:14:53.818
The right thing to do
is to find the Library.

230
00:14:53.893 --> 00:14:56.021
If that were the right
thing to do. Flynn Carsen.

231
00:14:56.095 --> 00:14:58.121
you'd be doing it.
Not reading about it.

232
00:14:58.197 --> 00:15:02.100
No. No. This is
your way of hiding.

233
00:15:05.238 --> 00:15:09.266
I bet... I bet that's what
you were like before all this.

234
00:15:10.777 --> 00:15:12.439
You hid in books.

235
00:15:14.113 --> 00:15:19.074
That's the life from which Judson
pulled you. That's what you were.

236
00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:23.050
Judson and Charlene.

237
00:15:25.658 --> 00:15:27.786
they made you what you are.

238
00:15:35.835 --> 00:15:38.964
Well. I'm gonna
be dead tomorrow.

239
00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:47.012
So. how would they want
you to spend your last day?

240
00:15:55.221 --> 00:15:57.918
They'd want me to save
the world one more time.

241
00:16:01.894 --> 00:16:05.194
So. tell me. Librarian.
how are you gonna do that?

242
00:16:08.801 --> 00:16:09.860
You

243
00:16:12.305 --> 00:16:13.364
are...

244
00:16:15.675 --> 00:16:16.675
Key!

245
00:16:19.045 --> 00:16:20.377
(CHUCKLING)

246
00:16:21.981 --> 00:16:24.280
I'm henge and key.

247
00:16:24.417 --> 00:16:27.945
She said "key." She
called Excalibur a key.

248
00:16:28.054 --> 00:16:30.523
She didn't say "sword."
she didn't say "weapon."

249
00:16:30.590 --> 00:16:31.867
She said "key."
and think about it.

250
00:16:31.891 --> 00:16:34.470
You're the Serpent Brotherhood. you
wanna bring magic back into the world.

251
00:16:34.494 --> 00:16:36.588
How are you gonna do
that with just one sword?

252
00:16:36.662 --> 00:16:37.940
COLONEL BAIRD:
Excalibur is pretty powerful.

253
00:16:37.964 --> 00:16:39.107
STONE: But it's
still just a sword.

254
00:16:39.131 --> 00:16:42.693
I mean. Excalibur against a tank?
An F-15. I'm betting on the military.

255
00:16:42.768 --> 00:16:44.703
That's right. It's
not an end goal.

256
00:16:44.770 --> 00:16:47.001
It's a key. And
what does a key do?

257
00:16:47.073 --> 00:16:48.439
- Jones!
- It goes in a lock.

258
00:16:48.508 --> 00:16:50.152
That's right. and we all
remember the legend.

259
00:16:50.176 --> 00:16:53.340
Excalibur was locked in once
before. it had to be pulled free.

260
00:16:53.412 --> 00:16:55.711
You must be feeling better.
You're not making any sense!

261
00:16:55.781 --> 00:16:57.147
The stone.

262
00:16:57.216 --> 00:16:59.194
The legend is Arthur pulled
Excalibur from the stone.

263
00:16:59.218 --> 00:17:02.313
After it had been charged with
magic. And where is that stone. Stone?

264
00:17:02.388 --> 00:17:06.189
If Arthur was Roman. it'd be at the
biggest Empire settlement in Britain.

265
00:17:06.259 --> 00:17:08.319
Londinium. Modern London.

266
00:17:08.828 --> 00:17:09.828
Ha!

267
00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:15.199
Look. there's a big ley line
running right underneath.

268
00:17:16.002 --> 00:17:17.903
Come on! Let's
go get that stone.

269
00:17:18.104 --> 00:17:19.231
Whoa. Us. too?

270
00:17:22.542 --> 00:17:25.706
Well. they've got the most
powerful weapon in the world.

271
00:17:26.579 --> 00:17:29.777
Judson's gone. Charlene's gone. The
Library's gone. I'm bleeding to death.

272
00:17:29.849 --> 00:17:32.876
So. yeah. working alone doesn't
seem like the best idea right now.

273
00:17:32.952 --> 00:17:34.978
Good. you're leaving. I
can get back to my work.

274
00:17:35.054 --> 00:17:39.492
Jenkins. book us tickets to
London. I'd do it myself. but I'm dying.

275
00:17:44.297 --> 00:17:45.788
Hey. Excuse me.

276
00:17:45.865 --> 00:17:48.232
You didn't turn off the
glowy globe. You got...

277
00:17:50.469 --> 00:17:51.469
(SIGHS)

278
00:17:53.105 --> 00:17:54.471
Hope it's on a timer.

279
00:18:00.546 --> 00:18:02.606
FLYNN: There's a magical
stone out there somewhere.

280
00:18:02.682 --> 00:18:04.412
I've got about 12
hours before I'm dead.

281
00:18:04.483 --> 00:18:07.214
and the end of the world
will probably come before that.

282
00:18:07.286 --> 00:18:09.152
- Full day ahead.
- How do we find the stone?

283
00:18:09.221 --> 00:18:10.314
What we need is a compass.

284
00:18:10.389 --> 00:18:13.450
The stone that Excalibur was
pulled from is almost pure magic.

285
00:18:13.526 --> 00:18:15.688
It should attract any
other magic item in the city.

286
00:18:15.761 --> 00:18:19.664
Let's just take another magic artifact.
rig it into the compass. Piece of cake.

287
00:18:19.732 --> 00:18:22.531
It is a piece of cake 'cause
I know just the artifact.

288
00:18:31.911 --> 00:18:34.608
GUIDE: Move this way. please.
ladies and gentlemen. This way.

289
00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:38.412
Now the Imperial State
Crown was made in 1937...

290
00:18:42.288 --> 00:18:44.587
- The Crown Jewels.
- We are not...

291
00:18:44.657 --> 00:18:46.148
FLYNN: Shh.

292
00:18:47.026 --> 00:18:50.793
We are not stealing the Crown
Jewels of the British monarchy.

293
00:18:50.863 --> 00:18:52.229
Of course not.

294
00:18:53.232 --> 00:18:54.757
We're stealing that one.

295
00:18:55.001 --> 00:18:56.993
The Star of Marrakech.

296
00:18:57.069 --> 00:18:59.470
John Dee used it to save
the life of Elizabeth the First

297
00:18:59.538 --> 00:19:02.474
from magical assassination.
Actually. really funny story...

298
00:19:02.541 --> 00:19:04.669
So. we're not stealing
the Crown Jewels.

299
00:19:04.744 --> 00:19:08.772
We're stealing a priceless artifact
from right next to the Crown Jewels.

300
00:19:08.848 --> 00:19:10.009
Oh. not we.

301
00:19:10.116 --> 00:19:11.175
(MOUTHING)

302
00:19:12.985 --> 00:19:14.865
(WHISPERS) Now I know
why the Library chose you.

303
00:19:17.890 --> 00:19:19.756
Vibration detectors
on the glass.

304
00:19:19.825 --> 00:19:22.488
Got a pressure plate. Can
tell when the weight changes.

305
00:19:22.962 --> 00:19:24.072
It's actually not too difficult.

306
00:19:24.096 --> 00:19:26.531
Please. don't let this be
something too unsavory.

307
00:19:26.599 --> 00:19:27.599
No. not at all.

308
00:19:28.968 --> 00:19:30.368
We just need to
steal a wheelchair.

309
00:19:47.987 --> 00:19:50.115
I can't believe I'm doing this.

310
00:19:50.189 --> 00:19:52.784
Really? All you do is
push people around.

311
00:19:56.896 --> 00:19:57.920
(GASPS) Oh!

312
00:19:57.997 --> 00:20:00.375
- I'm so sorry. That was an accident.
- That's the third time this week.

313
00:20:00.399 --> 00:20:02.044
- Are you okay?
- I keep telling you to slow down.

314
00:20:02.068 --> 00:20:03.812
- Don't yell. please don't yell.
- It's not a race. Not a race.

315
00:20:03.836 --> 00:20:05.270
Sorry.

316
00:20:05.438 --> 00:20:07.202
(ALARM BEEPING)

317
00:20:19.719 --> 00:20:23.053
Seriously? You're gonna put your gum
on a stone worth seven million euros?

318
00:20:24.824 --> 00:20:26.690
(SPEAKING LATIN)

319
00:20:33.566 --> 00:20:35.592
That's pretty...

320
00:20:41.907 --> 00:20:43.205
(ALARM BLARING)

321
00:20:45.644 --> 00:20:46.644
COLONEL BAIRD: Where to?

322
00:20:47.179 --> 00:20:48.272
Follow the gem.

323
00:20:55.888 --> 00:20:56.912
Lost 'em.

324
00:20:57.623 --> 00:20:59.701
We've got about five minutes
before the police show up.

325
00:20:59.725 --> 00:21:02.752
- (STRAINING) The gem can find it in three.
- And then?

326
00:21:02.828 --> 00:21:05.855
We're gonna have to keep them
from putting Excalibur back in the stone.

327
00:21:05.931 --> 00:21:08.196
Why would they want to put
Excalibur back into the stone?

328
00:21:13.472 --> 00:21:14.816
DULAQUE: It would
be like a jump start.

329
00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:17.400
CASSANDRA: Like jump-starting
a car? DULAQUE: Exactly.

330
00:21:17.476 --> 00:21:20.412
Excalibur is one of the few
great items of magic remaining.

331
00:21:21.213 --> 00:21:23.114
It contains unbelievable power.

332
00:21:23.182 --> 00:21:27.017
Power that was siphoned from
the ley lines of magic. centuries ago.

333
00:21:27.086 --> 00:21:29.282
And now all those
ley lines are dormant.

334
00:21:29.355 --> 00:21:31.654
But if we were to
suddenly shock them

335
00:21:31.724 --> 00:21:34.523
by returning Excalibur's
power back to the earth.

336
00:21:34.593 --> 00:21:37.586
it would begin a chain reaction.
The energy would build on itself.

337
00:21:37.663 --> 00:21:40.360
Magic would spread back
out through the ley lines

338
00:21:40.432 --> 00:21:45.097
and magic would
return to the entire world.

339
00:21:48.407 --> 00:21:51.605
This was a river. you
know. The Tyburn.

340
00:21:52.978 --> 00:21:55.004
I remember when
it ran above ground.

341
00:21:56.816 --> 00:21:58.250
Through meadows.

342
00:22:03.923 --> 00:22:06.518
We found the chamber
holding the stone by using sonar.

343
00:22:06.592 --> 00:22:08.857
Decided coming in from
the side was the best bet.

344
00:22:08.928 --> 00:22:13.389
Required drilling. air recycling. but
still better than coming in from the top.

345
00:22:13.465 --> 00:22:15.457
There are magical traps
at the proper entrance.

346
00:22:15.534 --> 00:22:17.366
plus the human security.

347
00:22:18.137 --> 00:22:19.137
Human security?

348
00:22:19.205 --> 00:22:22.485
DULAQUE: You didn't think the location of
the stone was a complete secret. did you?

349
00:22:22.842 --> 00:22:25.710
The royal family's been
hiding it for centuries.

350
00:22:31.784 --> 00:22:32.843
Is that...

351
00:22:35.988 --> 00:22:38.355
That's Buckingham Palace.

352
00:22:38.424 --> 00:22:40.552
Good news. There's a
charity event on tonight.

353
00:22:40.626 --> 00:22:41.803
I bet I can forge
us some invites.

354
00:22:41.827 --> 00:22:43.187
We just robbed
the Tower of London

355
00:22:43.229 --> 00:22:46.063
and now you want us to
break into Buckingham Palace?

356
00:22:46.131 --> 00:22:48.259
It's more fraud than it
is breaking and entering.

357
00:22:48.334 --> 00:22:50.030
Listen to me. can
you make me a duke?

358
00:22:50.102 --> 00:22:51.263
- Sure.
- (SIGHS)

359
00:22:51.337 --> 00:22:55.365
What's next? The Vatican? The
Taj Mahal? The White House?

360
00:22:57.276 --> 00:22:59.541
She'll be back. Maybe.

361
00:23:02.848 --> 00:23:04.476
(CROWD CHATTERING)

362
00:23:10.189 --> 00:23:11.316
You okay. cowboy?

363
00:23:11.924 --> 00:23:13.017
My first suit.

364
00:23:14.193 --> 00:23:15.217
I'm rocking it.

365
00:23:15.294 --> 00:23:19.095
Where is Baird? She's not
gonna get in without an invitation.

366
00:23:20.332 --> 00:23:22.858
- Good evening.
- Welcome. Good evening.

367
00:23:27.006 --> 00:23:28.246
And these are your invitations?

368
00:23:29.775 --> 00:23:30.775
Could you wait here?

369
00:23:32.011 --> 00:23:33.479
And please don't try to leave.

370
00:23:36.181 --> 00:23:37.274
You know what I'm thinking?

371
00:23:38.851 --> 00:23:40.581
That your forgeries are crap?

372
00:23:40.653 --> 00:23:43.714
No. I'm thinking I can run faster
than you 'cause you've been stabbed.

373
00:23:46.492 --> 00:23:47.652
FLYNN: All right. here we go.

374
00:23:48.594 --> 00:23:49.653
(CLEARS THROAT)

375
00:23:51.931 --> 00:23:53.171
COLONEL BAIRD: They're with me.

376
00:24:04.209 --> 00:24:06.678
Orders from the director of
counter-terrorism. Stay sharp.

377
00:24:08.013 --> 00:24:09.538
MAN: All right.
gentlemen. Welcome.

378
00:24:25.731 --> 00:24:28.599
The royal family must have
created an access to get to the stone.

379
00:24:28.667 --> 00:24:31.603
Look for a secret passageway.
Something out of the ordinary.

380
00:24:35.507 --> 00:24:38.272
Undercover. Librarian.
Can't hold you up all night.

381
00:24:39.545 --> 00:24:40.985
How about for the
next five minutes?

382
00:24:48.787 --> 00:24:51.985
All right. look for anything out of place.
We've got to find the secret passage.

383
00:24:52.057 --> 00:24:54.219
Well. if we find it. it's
not so secret then. is it?

384
00:24:54.293 --> 00:24:56.762
GUIDE: Profoundly influenced
by the landscape artist.

385
00:24:56.829 --> 00:25:00.095
Robert Bevan. who
originated this style.

386
00:25:00.165 --> 00:25:03.465
Notice the subtle use of the color
purple in the upper right hand corner.

387
00:25:03.535 --> 00:25:04.535
Hey. hi. Pardon me.

388
00:25:04.603 --> 00:25:08.665
Did you imply that Turner was influenced
by Bevan rather than Robert Wilson?

389
00:25:08.741 --> 00:25:12.178
I did not imply. I mean.
Wilson was a bit of an influence.

390
00:25:13.512 --> 00:25:15.912
Surely. you've read Turner's
correspondence with John Ruskin?

391
00:25:16.315 --> 00:25:18.511
The preeminent art
critic of the 1800s.

392
00:25:18.584 --> 00:25:23.750
He was part of an unbroken line of
influence from Wilson through Turner...

393
00:25:23.822 --> 00:25:25.552
- Champagne. sir?
- Hey. How are you?

394
00:25:25.624 --> 00:25:27.184
- I'm well. Thank you. sir.
- Thank you.

395
00:25:27.593 --> 00:25:29.084
Actually. can I get a beer?

396
00:25:32.031 --> 00:25:33.329
Hello. gorgeous.

397
00:25:42.307 --> 00:25:43.427
COLONEL BAIRD: This is nice.

398
00:25:45.778 --> 00:25:47.212
Yes. it is.

399
00:25:47.279 --> 00:25:48.941
We can completely
move around the room

400
00:25:49.014 --> 00:25:51.745
and check for secret passages
without seeming suspicious.

401
00:25:53.018 --> 00:25:54.213
Exactly that.

402
00:25:55.387 --> 00:25:57.117
Do you think Stone
and Ezekiel are...

403
00:25:57.189 --> 00:25:59.283
Not doing what they're
supposed to be doing?

404
00:25:59.358 --> 00:26:00.792
- Probably not.
- (CHUCKLES)

405
00:26:01.226 --> 00:26:03.338
We've dropped them into a
completely ridiculous situation

406
00:26:03.362 --> 00:26:04.728
with absolutely no training.

407
00:26:05.230 --> 00:26:07.028
It's what happened to me.

408
00:26:07.099 --> 00:26:08.499
They don't train the Librarian?

409
00:26:09.968 --> 00:26:11.766
Well. how'd you do
on your first mission?

410
00:26:11.837 --> 00:26:14.966
FLYNN: (LAUGHS) I got completely
distracted. nearly died about nine times.

411
00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:18.204
And would have if it hadn't
been for my Guardian.

412
00:26:21.046 --> 00:26:23.982
For what it's worth.
I'm glad you didn't die.

413
00:26:25.617 --> 00:26:28.382
I found out there's magic
in the world. I owe you that.

414
00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:34.886
We should schedule a dance sometime
when you're not slowly bleeding to death.

415
00:26:36.795 --> 00:26:38.286
Let's save the world first.

416
00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:41.495
- You ever get used to saving the world?
- (CHUCKLES)

417
00:26:42.835 --> 00:26:45.771
I don't even bother to put
it on my to-do list anymore.

418
00:26:51.210 --> 00:26:53.941
Mr. Dulaque. we cannot thank
you enough for your donation.

419
00:26:54.646 --> 00:26:58.640
Ambassador. I've always said.
"If you want to change the world.

420
00:26:58.717 --> 00:27:02.017
"you can't wait around for
other people to do it for you."

421
00:27:02.087 --> 00:27:03.646
We're running out of time.

422
00:27:06.024 --> 00:27:07.686
Get me through that wall.

423
00:27:09.228 --> 00:27:10.228
(GRUNTS)

424
00:27:14.700 --> 00:27:15.700
(GRUNTS)

425
00:27:20.339 --> 00:27:22.103
MAN: Run the wire down here.

426
00:27:25.744 --> 00:27:27.645
Bring in the lights
and the air hoses.

427
00:27:27.713 --> 00:27:29.443
(MEN SHOUTING IN DISTANCE)

428
00:27:38.991 --> 00:27:40.619
The stone of King Arthur.

429
00:27:44.196 --> 00:27:45.892
I want everything in here now!

430
00:27:54.439 --> 00:27:55.799
- Cut through this.
- Right. ma'am.

431
00:27:59.011 --> 00:28:00.104
(SCREAMS)

432
00:28:01.547 --> 00:28:03.573
Right. New plan.

433
00:28:07.986 --> 00:28:09.113
What is this?

434
00:28:14.193 --> 00:28:15.217
It's high Enochian.

435
00:28:23.802 --> 00:28:27.295
It's a mathematical language
based on ancient Greek and Hebrew.

436
00:28:31.410 --> 00:28:32.742
And you can crack it?

437
00:28:33.812 --> 00:28:34.836
Given time.

438
00:28:37.783 --> 00:28:39.445
Take all the time you need.

439
00:28:43.388 --> 00:28:44.856
MAN: The crown. ma'am.

440
00:29:10.315 --> 00:29:12.327
They're running standard
counter-terrorism along the perimeter

441
00:29:12.351 --> 00:29:14.081
and soft threat
assessment on the inside.

442
00:29:14.152 --> 00:29:16.246
which means their
attention's on the VIPs.

443
00:29:16.321 --> 00:29:19.001
And the interior guards are guarding
the doorways and the corridors.

444
00:29:19.057 --> 00:29:20.582
which begs one question.

445
00:29:20.659 --> 00:29:22.890
Why is that guard
standing at the wall?

446
00:29:27.899 --> 00:29:31.165
That coat of arms belonged to
John Sheffield. Duke of Normanby.

447
00:29:31.236 --> 00:29:33.171
Original architect of
Buckingham House.

448
00:29:34.539 --> 00:29:36.030
- Secret door.
- Secret door.

449
00:29:38.510 --> 00:29:41.207
I think I might be fading a
little faster than I thought.

450
00:29:44.416 --> 00:29:48.683
Certainly you can't argue that
Joseph Turner simply changed styles.

451
00:29:48.754 --> 00:29:50.531
STONE: I'm not arguing
with you. I'm telling you.

452
00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:53.286
In the plates of <i>Liber Studiorum.</i>
you can see the reflections...

453
00:29:53.358 --> 00:29:54.621
Stone. gotta go.

454
00:29:55.994 --> 00:29:57.705
And so. that's pretty
much exactly why I had to...

455
00:29:57.729 --> 00:29:58.992
Really?

456
00:30:00.299 --> 00:30:01.699
- You. uh. dropped these.
- (GASPS)

457
00:30:03.068 --> 00:30:04.092
Oh. Mary...

458
00:30:04.202 --> 00:30:05.602
- And these.
- (WOMEN GASP)

459
00:30:15.580 --> 00:30:16.741
(PHONE KEYS CLICKING)

460
00:30:18.984 --> 00:30:20.984
MAN VIA COMM: <i>Alarm in
sector four. Please respond.</i>

461
00:30:25.624 --> 00:30:27.490
Buckingham Palace.

462
00:30:29.328 --> 00:30:31.263
I was really expecting
a better secret door.

463
00:30:31.330 --> 00:30:32.559
Oh. write a letter. Let's go.

464
00:30:34.433 --> 00:30:35.765
You ain't looking so hot.

465
00:30:35.834 --> 00:30:38.099
No matter what
happens. get the crown.

466
00:30:38.170 --> 00:30:41.140
If you drop. we'll
leave you and move on.

467
00:30:42.374 --> 00:30:46.072
Wait. Why would you go there?
That's a horrible thing to say.

468
00:30:55.020 --> 00:30:56.545
- (CLICKS)
- (RUMBLING)

469
00:30:58.724 --> 00:31:00.488
(HUMMING)

470
00:31:03.161 --> 00:31:04.595
(CLANKING)

471
00:31:10.569 --> 00:31:12.697
Nice work. little Librarian.

472
00:31:13.939 --> 00:31:17.239
Palaces have dungeons.
right? Find a cell. stick her in it.

473
00:31:17.309 --> 00:31:18.675
- Yes. ma'am.
- What?

474
00:31:18.744 --> 00:31:20.337
You said you were
gonna help people.

475
00:31:20.412 --> 00:31:22.779
We are. We're bringing
magic back to the world.

476
00:31:22.848 --> 00:31:24.749
The whole world. all at once.

477
00:31:25.217 --> 00:31:29.780
Technology ends. magic
returns and we control it.

478
00:31:29.855 --> 00:31:31.153
Come on! Move.

479
00:31:38.096 --> 00:31:40.759
- Return to us. oh ancient world of wonders.
- (ZAPPING)

480
00:31:42.667 --> 00:31:45.432
Return and be ours!

481
00:31:45.504 --> 00:31:46.733
(ZAPPING AND CRACKLING)

482
00:31:55.113 --> 00:31:56.638
STONE: It's the old section.

483
00:32:00.419 --> 00:32:01.853
George the Third's time.

484
00:32:02.521 --> 00:32:04.251
- (CRACKLING)
- Uh-oh.

485
00:32:04.623 --> 00:32:05.921
(ZAPPING)

486
00:32:15.534 --> 00:32:18.504
Welcome back.

487
00:32:19.704 --> 00:32:21.263
The sword's rejoined the stone.

488
00:32:24.676 --> 00:32:27.145
(GROANS) Magic's coming back.

489
00:32:27.212 --> 00:32:28.510
That's a magic wound.

490
00:32:29.281 --> 00:32:30.943
Hello. darling.

491
00:32:33.185 --> 00:32:35.780
An 1811 Château d'Yquem.
Stole one of these once.

492
00:32:35.854 --> 00:32:37.322
Worth about $100.000.

493
00:32:37.389 --> 00:32:40.549
Not a chance it is staying in a wine
cellar. Don't care whose wine cellar it is.

494
00:32:42.894 --> 00:32:43.953
Hang on.

495
00:32:54.239 --> 00:32:55.764
(RUMBLING)

496
00:33:20.432 --> 00:33:21.559
We're not alone.

497
00:33:24.069 --> 00:33:25.765
- They tunneled in from...
- Shh.

498
00:33:26.071 --> 00:33:30.406
(WHISPERS) They tunneled in from the
side. That's much smarter than what we did.

499
00:33:34.746 --> 00:33:37.215
LAMIA: We have worked
long and hard to achieve

500
00:33:37.282 --> 00:33:39.911
what stands before
us today. brothers.

501
00:33:44.523 --> 00:33:48.824
The goal of returning
magic to the world.

502
00:33:49.427 --> 00:33:50.725
it is but moments away.

503
00:33:51.997 --> 00:33:53.431
(ZAPPING)

504
00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:03.306
Okay. we got trained killers.

505
00:34:03.375 --> 00:34:04.468
One of them's got a crown

506
00:34:04.543 --> 00:34:07.377
that's allowing her to control
the most deadly weapon on earth.

507
00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:11.106
Ideas. ideas. ideas. ideas?

508
00:34:11.182 --> 00:34:12.480
CASSANDRA: I have some ideas.

509
00:34:23.828 --> 00:34:24.887
Hey. kid.

510
00:34:26.932 --> 00:34:29.925
Uh. no. thanks. You
already sold us out once.

511
00:34:30.068 --> 00:34:32.970
She had her reasons.
Let's get her out of there.

512
00:34:33.038 --> 00:34:34.301
Wait a minute.

513
00:34:34.372 --> 00:34:36.500
Oh. no. Oh. no. No. no. no. no.

514
00:34:36.575 --> 00:34:38.976
You all ganged up on me and
said. "Let's do this together."

515
00:34:39.044 --> 00:34:41.570
So. let's do this together.
Get her out of there.

516
00:34:43.081 --> 00:34:44.081
Come on.

517
00:34:46.251 --> 00:34:49.050
- Okay. what's the big idea?
- Okay. come here.

518
00:34:52.057 --> 00:34:53.081
Come on.

519
00:34:54.025 --> 00:34:58.861
Okay. so. that's the drill that
they cool with ice-water pipes.

520
00:34:59.831 --> 00:35:01.299
That's the air recycler.

521
00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:04.612
And then the electrical wires
are in the generator and then...

522
00:35:04.636 --> 00:35:07.936
I got you. Metal pipes. Very
good plan. Distraction. then action.

523
00:35:08.006 --> 00:35:10.305
This is gonna work. But
it's gonna take all of us.

524
00:35:10.375 --> 00:35:11.809
Stone. your knowledge
of mechanics.

525
00:35:11.876 --> 00:35:14.971
You need to re-route that ice water
coolant into the warm air recycler.

526
00:35:15.046 --> 00:35:16.344
<i>That's gonna give us our cover.</i>

527
00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:20.313
(MACHINE WHIRS)

528
00:35:22.887 --> 00:35:24.446
(HISSING)

529
00:35:27.492 --> 00:35:30.519
- LAMIA: Librarians. Find them.
- Yes. ma'am. Come on. come on!

530
00:35:30.595 --> 00:35:32.086
Ezekiel. you're hacking.

531
00:35:32.163 --> 00:35:33.722
You gotta rewire
that generator panel

532
00:35:33.798 --> 00:35:36.825
and give me alternating current.
very strong. when I yell for it

533
00:35:36.901 --> 00:35:38.927
<i>at the frequency that
Cassandra gives you.</i>

534
00:35:39.004 --> 00:35:40.233
Six-Seven-One-Four.

535
00:35:41.106 --> 00:35:43.346
Eve. you gotta keep them
distracted while I get to Lamia.

536
00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:50.441
(GRUNTING)

537
00:35:57.922 --> 00:35:59.288
(GRUNTING)

538
00:36:04.663 --> 00:36:06.291
I hear you. Librarian.

539
00:36:09.501 --> 00:36:12.471
Give me the crown. Stop this.

540
00:36:13.405 --> 00:36:14.429
Stop this?

541
00:36:16.207 --> 00:36:17.334
(GRUNTING)

542
00:36:19.310 --> 00:36:20.310
Ow!

543
00:36:21.946 --> 00:36:23.786
MAN: Hey. what are you
doing? STONE: Watch out!

544
00:36:28.386 --> 00:36:30.252
Magic is returning to the world.

545
00:36:30.321 --> 00:36:32.119
It's flowing out
through the ley lines.

546
00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:34.489
creeping back into
every corner of this planet.

547
00:36:34.559 --> 00:36:38.052
Magic you control is
power I can't let you have.

548
00:36:40.632 --> 00:36:41.759
(GRUNTING)

549
00:36:46.204 --> 00:36:48.435
- (GROANING)
- (LAMIA CHUCKLING)

550
00:36:48.940 --> 00:36:53.901
And how are you going to stop us?
Hmm? With your little knock-off Librarians?

551
00:36:54.112 --> 00:36:55.774
(GRUNTING)

552
00:36:57.615 --> 00:37:00.813
One doomed by her
gift. one who fled his gift.

553
00:37:00.885 --> 00:37:02.251
one who abuses it.

554
00:37:03.188 --> 00:37:04.850
Or your little soldier girl?

555
00:37:08.626 --> 00:37:12.495
No. I'm the Librarian.

556
00:37:21.506 --> 00:37:24.032
Librarians win with knowledge.

557
00:37:24.109 --> 00:37:25.839
- Librarians win with science.
- (SIGHS)

558
00:37:27.378 --> 00:37:29.677
Librarians win with
electromagnets!

559
00:37:38.256 --> 00:37:39.383
(CRACKLING)

560
00:37:42.360 --> 00:37:43.419
Cal. come!

561
00:37:44.829 --> 00:37:45.829
(YELLS)

562
00:38:01.412 --> 00:38:02.812
(EXCALIBUR WHIMPERING)

563
00:38:15.660 --> 00:38:16.923
What's happening?

564
00:38:16.995 --> 00:38:19.157
Most of the magic's
gone back into the earth.

565
00:38:21.866 --> 00:38:23.266
He's dying.

566
00:38:28.573 --> 00:38:29.632
I think we both are.

567
00:38:30.508 --> 00:38:31.635
(MOANS)

568
00:38:35.079 --> 00:38:39.175
Listen. the power that's
left is almost all raw magic.

569
00:38:43.988 --> 00:38:47.425
It can help you.
It can save you.

570
00:38:50.461 --> 00:38:52.521
- Flynn.
- It's okay.

571
00:38:55.166 --> 00:38:57.567
Judson's gone. Charlene's gone.

572
00:38:58.837 --> 00:38:59.896
Excalibur's dying.

573
00:39:02.073 --> 00:39:03.405
It's time.

574
00:39:04.576 --> 00:39:05.576
Flynn...

575
00:39:06.945 --> 00:39:08.538
Just touch it to your head.

576
00:39:09.981 --> 00:39:11.279
(SOBS)

577
00:39:24.462 --> 00:39:25.521
(GASPING)

578
00:39:36.708 --> 00:39:37.708
(SOBBING) Oh. God!

579
00:39:44.782 --> 00:39:45.875
(BABBLES)

580
00:39:47.285 --> 00:39:48.446
(GRUNTS)

581
00:39:54.792 --> 00:39:55.919
(GASPS)

582
00:39:57.028 --> 00:40:00.863
No. No. it was
supposed to be for you.

583
00:40:03.935 --> 00:40:05.801
You already have saved me.

584
00:40:10.808 --> 00:40:12.436
(WHIMPERING)

585
00:40:19.050 --> 00:40:21.076
(EXCALIBUR WHIMPERING)

586
00:40:24.889 --> 00:40:28.826
It's okay. It's
okay. old friend.

587
00:41:03.227 --> 00:41:09.167
Once again. magic is defeated by
wisdom. proving that there is nothing.

588
00:41:09.233 --> 00:41:13.364
there is no situation. that
can't be solved by thinking.

589
00:41:13.805 --> 00:41:14.864
Get your hands up!

590
00:41:18.509 --> 00:41:20.205
- So...
- I'm thinking.

591
00:41:23.414 --> 00:41:24.643
Colonel... Colonel Baird?

592
00:41:24.882 --> 00:41:26.077
Hawkins?

593
00:41:26.351 --> 00:41:27.785
No. no.

594
00:41:27.852 --> 00:41:30.532
- Sorry to interrupt your thinking.
- No. no. that's okay. Go ahead.

595
00:41:31.255 --> 00:41:33.747
Gentlemen. funny story.

596
00:41:49.407 --> 00:41:51.000
Your airline tickets.

597
00:41:52.677 --> 00:41:53.940
That's mighty generous of you.

598
00:41:54.012 --> 00:41:55.212
JENKINS: Ah. well. not really.

599
00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:58.306
All the miles a Librarian
racks up every year.

600
00:41:58.383 --> 00:42:02.377
you could trade those in for a seat on a
flight to the secret moon colony. (CHUCKLES)

601
00:42:06.391 --> 00:42:08.257
Oh. you don't
know... Well. uh...

602
00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:10.160
Huh.

603
00:42:10.528 --> 00:42:11.723
STONE: So. that's it?

604
00:42:12.363 --> 00:42:14.264
For you. yup.

605
00:42:14.332 --> 00:42:16.858
But we have transferred
some rather generous...

606
00:42:16.934 --> 00:42:18.846
- Not too generous.
- Stipends into your accounts

607
00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:20.930
and arranged for
your travel home.

608
00:42:21.339 --> 00:42:22.637
Thank you very much.

609
00:42:23.975 --> 00:42:27.468
I don't think it's fair or safe to
involve you in this life any longer.

610
00:42:30.014 --> 00:42:33.610
A life that would have been ours
had luck broken just a little differently.

611
00:42:33.718 --> 00:42:35.880
Mmm. Maybe not.

612
00:42:37.522 --> 00:42:39.354
- So. back to our lives.
- Yup.

613
00:42:39.957 --> 00:42:41.858
Knowing that magic is real.

614
00:42:41.926 --> 00:42:44.157
- Knowing the world...
- CASSANDRA: is so big.

615
00:42:44.762 --> 00:42:50.326
The world is so big. I mean.
what if we can't just move on?

616
00:42:57.842 --> 00:43:01.210
- Well. Jenkins.
- Yes.

617
00:43:04.348 --> 00:43:06.340
You've also all signed
non-disclosure forms

618
00:43:06.417 --> 00:43:08.462
so as not to tell anyone of
the events which occurred.

619
00:43:08.486 --> 00:43:10.819
the existence of the
Library and the Librarian.

620
00:43:10.888 --> 00:43:15.258
of magic and secret
conspiracies. and well. anything.

621
00:43:15.893 --> 00:43:16.986
Or else?

622
00:43:17.061 --> 00:43:20.657
Please. tell people about the
magic Library and Excalibur

623
00:43:20.731 --> 00:43:23.895
and how you broke into Buckingham
Palace because King Arthur is really Roman.

624
00:43:23.968 --> 00:43:26.904
I'll come visit you. make sure
the straitjacket's not too tight.

625
00:43:27.872 --> 00:43:28.965
Okay.

626
00:43:29.907 --> 00:43:31.307
What about temporal resonance?

627
00:43:31.375 --> 00:43:33.735
- If we could get a crystal skull and...
- Sir. sir. I've...

628
00:43:34.645 --> 00:43:36.341
I've tried everything.

629
00:43:36.414 --> 00:43:39.475
The card catalog is still
anchored to this reality.

630
00:43:39.550 --> 00:43:43.487
It can still access the records of
the Library. books. manuscripts.

631
00:43:43.554 --> 00:43:49.255
but the Library itself and all of its
artifacts are cut loose from this world.

632
00:43:49.327 --> 00:43:54.561
The Library is adrift in time and
space. The Library. sir. is lost.

633
00:44:18.789 --> 00:44:19.916
(KNOCKS TWICE)

634
00:44:20.658 --> 00:44:22.217
- Hello. Flynn.
- (LAUGHS)

635
00:44:24.595 --> 00:44:25.595
Judson.

636
00:44:27.331 --> 00:44:29.357
- Is the Library...
- Intact?

637
00:44:30.301 --> 00:44:31.360
Certainly.

638
00:44:32.203 --> 00:44:33.728
And Charlene?

639
00:44:33.804 --> 00:44:34.863
She's with the Library.

640
00:44:35.606 --> 00:44:37.802
She's tougher than
she looks. you know.

641
00:44:37.875 --> 00:44:39.605
- And you?
- I'm. uh...

642
00:44:41.946 --> 00:44:44.142
My time is done.

643
00:44:45.550 --> 00:44:47.075
You're ready to move on.

644
00:44:47.151 --> 00:44:49.620
No. You're ready.

645
00:44:56.294 --> 00:44:58.320
You know. Judson. I never. um...

646
00:45:01.432 --> 00:45:02.900
I never had a father.

647
00:45:03.668 --> 00:45:05.830
And I never had a son.

648
00:45:07.905 --> 00:45:11.398
Well. now we're both liars.

649
00:45:15.880 --> 00:45:17.348
I'm gonna find the Library.

650
00:45:19.083 --> 00:45:22.110
I'm the Librarian.
Nothing's impossible.

651
00:45:22.186 --> 00:45:25.384
The Serpent Brotherhood failed.

652
00:45:25.456 --> 00:45:29.917
but they released an enormous
amount of magic into the world.

653
00:45:29.994 --> 00:45:33.453
Things are going to
get a little mad out there.

654
00:45:34.065 --> 00:45:36.193
You're in charge now

655
00:45:36.267 --> 00:45:41.934
and you're not going to have
time to search for the Library.

656
00:45:43.541 --> 00:45:47.069
No. not if I try to do it alone.

657
00:45:47.144 --> 00:45:49.545
Flynn. I'll always be...

658
00:45:52.283 --> 00:45:53.717
COLONEL BAIRD: Flynn?

659
00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:00.888
I'm the Librarian.

660
00:46:04.128 --> 00:46:05.460
I'm in charge.

661
00:46:05.863 --> 00:46:08.128
Oh. Okay.

662
00:46:10.635 --> 00:46:13.036
So. it's time I started
making up some new rules.

663
00:46:29.520 --> 00:46:30.613
New plan.

664
00:46:34.592 --> 00:46:39.963
Although I suspect it's the
old plan. I'm just figuring it out.

665
00:46:40.031 --> 00:46:41.556
Open your envelopes.

666
00:46:41.632 --> 00:46:43.100
Our airline tickets?

667
00:46:47.838 --> 00:46:49.568
- Go ahead.
- I left mine back at...

668
00:46:49.640 --> 00:46:50.869
Look again.

669
00:47:04.955 --> 00:47:08.585
Just as I suspected. We
have a lot of work to do.

670
00:47:11.329 --> 00:47:15.630
I think that this will be a
perfect base of operations.

671
00:47:15.700 --> 00:47:18.067
You'll have access to the
archives. if not the artifacts.

672
00:47:18.135 --> 00:47:20.001
and Jenkins here will
teach you how to research

673
00:47:20.071 --> 00:47:22.131
and supervise your
training as Librarians.

674
00:47:22.206 --> 00:47:24.607
What are you talking about?
We do not train Librarians.

675
00:47:24.675 --> 00:47:27.042
Yes. and isn't that stupid?

676
00:47:27.111 --> 00:47:30.548
We take a highly intelligent but
totally unsuspecting individual.

677
00:47:30.614 --> 00:47:32.993
drop them in a world of magic
and then expect them not to die

678
00:47:33.017 --> 00:47:34.747
before they learn
where the toilet is.

679
00:47:34.819 --> 00:47:36.253
That is how it's
always been done.

680
00:47:36.320 --> 00:47:39.688
Now that I'm Librarian. we're
not doing it that way anymore.

681
00:47:39.757 --> 00:47:42.420
Meet the Librarianettes.

682
00:47:42.493 --> 00:47:45.327
No. Meet the
Librarians-in-training.

683
00:47:45.396 --> 00:47:47.558
The L-I-Ts. My little LITs.

684
00:47:48.265 --> 00:47:51.360
- (STAMMERS) But they're not qualified.
- Then we'll qualify them.

685
00:47:51.435 --> 00:47:53.131
I'll still handle the big stuff.

686
00:47:53.204 --> 00:47:56.402
They'll handle all the. you know.
slightly less apocalyptic stuff.

687
00:47:56.474 --> 00:48:01.242
And this will free me up to
find the Library and bring it back.

688
00:48:01.312 --> 00:48:02.473
That is impossible.

689
00:48:02.546 --> 00:48:05.482
Oh. Impossible. pipsy
posh. pipsy posh! Jenkins.

690
00:48:05.549 --> 00:48:09.008
People keep saying that as if we don't
eat the impossible for breakfast every day.

691
00:48:13.891 --> 00:48:16.520
I'm offering you
a life of mystery

692
00:48:18.863 --> 00:48:20.058
and misery.

693
00:48:21.265 --> 00:48:24.497
of loneliness and adventure.

694
00:48:31.108 --> 00:48:33.976
More than that. I'm offering you
an opportunity to make a difference.

695
00:48:35.212 --> 00:48:39.479
And to save the world every
week. twice before Friday.

696
00:48:41.685 --> 00:48:42.812
Are you in?

697
00:48:46.323 --> 00:48:47.985
- Even her?
- Yeah.

698
00:48:48.058 --> 00:48:52.189
She sacrificed her own life
to save Flynn's. I trust her.

699
00:48:57.301 --> 00:48:58.301
I'll give it shot.

700
00:48:59.937 --> 00:49:02.133
If we're helping people. sure.

701
00:49:02.206 --> 00:49:05.608
It will provide an opportunity
to steal new things. I'm in.

702
00:49:21.258 --> 00:49:23.454
Hey. It's your Library now.

703
00:49:24.995 --> 00:49:26.827
At least this little part of it.

704
00:49:28.165 --> 00:49:31.033
And don't worry. I'll be back
to check on you in a few weeks.

705
00:49:33.971 --> 00:49:35.269
Try not to die.

706
00:49:42.079 --> 00:49:43.274
Oh. joy.

707
00:49:45.616 --> 00:49:47.517
We'll need to find
them a Guardian.

708
00:49:47.585 --> 00:49:49.796
Stone's the only one who
can handle himself in a bar fight

709
00:49:49.820 --> 00:49:53.257
and I don't think you'll find too
many magical artifacts in dive bars.

710
00:49:53.324 --> 00:49:55.418
I've already found
their Guardian.

711
00:49:56.994 --> 00:50:00.021
Flynn. no. With Judson
gone. who can you trust?

712
00:50:00.097 --> 00:50:01.463
Well. that's just it.

713
00:50:03.534 --> 00:50:06.026
With Judson gone
and the Library gone.

714
00:50:07.238 --> 00:50:10.675
if anything were to happen
to me. they're the future.

715
00:50:13.210 --> 00:50:15.941
I haven't met anybody that
I trust in the last five years.

716
00:50:16.981 --> 00:50:19.849
I trust you to protect them.

717
00:50:21.452 --> 00:50:23.080
But I thought you
needed a Guardian.

718
00:50:23.954 --> 00:50:25.718
The Library chose
you to be a Guardian.

719
00:50:25.789 --> 00:50:30.352
I think the Library chose
you to be their Guardian.

720
00:50:31.896 --> 00:50:34.161
and Lord knows they're
gonna need protecting.

721
00:50:34.899 --> 00:50:36.492
Way more than I need.

722
00:50:38.202 --> 00:50:43.402
More than I want to be
traveling the world with you.

723
00:50:48.512 --> 00:50:50.811
Librarian and Guardian.

724
00:50:50.881 --> 00:50:53.112
The job's more important
than what we want.

725
00:50:53.884 --> 00:50:57.150
No. don't say that.
That's the old way.

726
00:50:57.488 --> 00:51:00.856
But for now. we have
to work separately.

727
00:51:12.503 --> 00:51:14.165
Come back alive. Librarian.

728
00:51:14.238 --> 00:51:19.336
I... Come back. Yeah. Uh...
Will come back and I'll talk...

729
00:51:20.377 --> 00:51:22.073
Sorry. I'm just...
I'll call you.

730
00:51:22.146 --> 00:51:24.424
No. I'll text you or will you text
me? Or we'll text each other.

731
00:51:24.448 --> 00:51:26.713
It'll be one of those things...

732
00:51:26.784 --> 00:51:28.650
Okay. so. yeah. Okay.

733
00:51:33.891 --> 00:51:37.658
JENKINS: Now. um. I know that
Flynn is technically the Librarian.

734
00:51:37.728 --> 00:51:42.029
- And I technically work for the Library.
- (SIGHS)

735
00:51:42.099 --> 00:51:44.864
Vis-à-vis. etcetera.
etcetera. the Librarian.

736
00:51:45.402 --> 00:51:48.270
- But I don't...
- Really have a choice.

737
00:51:49.073 --> 00:51:51.201
These three will be using
this as a base of operations

738
00:51:51.275 --> 00:51:52.752
and I'll be supervising
their security.

739
00:51:52.776 --> 00:51:56.440
So. make yourself useful

740
00:51:56.513 --> 00:51:58.379
or make yourself gone.

741
00:52:01.619 --> 00:52:03.679
- You're bluffing.
- STONE: Ooh.

742
00:52:04.388 --> 00:52:05.981
She doesn't bluff.

743
00:52:06.056 --> 00:52:08.525
Not so much threats as promises.

744
00:52:08.592 --> 00:52:10.857
Yeah. she can and
will kick your ass.

745
00:52:17.434 --> 00:52:19.194
I suppose there's
always the clippings book.

746
00:52:19.637 --> 00:52:20.969
What's a clippings book?

747
00:52:21.138 --> 00:52:23.698
Oh. child of the
annoying digital age.

748
00:52:23.774 --> 00:52:26.869
It is how we used to gather
information about news stories.

749
00:52:28.245 --> 00:52:31.579
Each page has clippings
from different sources

750
00:52:31.649 --> 00:52:33.845
detailing a bizarre mystery.

751
00:52:33.917 --> 00:52:36.887
Well. we really don't need a
book full of old newspaper articles.

752
00:52:36.954 --> 00:52:38.752
Oh. silly mid-western person.

753
00:52:38.822 --> 00:52:42.315
This clipping's book is
the Library's clippings book.

754
00:52:42.393 --> 00:52:44.862
Every night. there
is a new page.

755
00:52:44.928 --> 00:52:49.366
New information about a new
mystery happening that very day.

756
00:52:49.433 --> 00:52:51.334
Come. let's begin.

757
00:52:53.504 --> 00:52:54.631
(CHUCKLES)

758
00:52:55.005 --> 00:52:57.167
Oh. this is just fascinating.

759
00:53:03.847 --> 00:53:06.976
You will never solve
this one. (CHUCKLES)

760
00:53:11.255 --> 00:53:13.247
(MUSIC PLAYING)
